Title : John Brudenell-Bruce
Text : {{Use British (Oxford) English|date=August 2017}}
{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}
'''John Charles Brudenell-Bruce''', [[Order of the British Empire|MBE]], [[Venerable Order of Saint John|OStJ]] (6 March 1885 - 13 February 1960), was a [[diplomat]] in the British service and a [[politician]] who served during the years immediately after the reintroduction of [[democracy]] in the [[British Virgin Islands]] in 1950.  
[[File:John Charles Brundell-Bruce.jpg|alt=Picture taken by Paula Mcinnis|thumb|John Charles Brundell-Bruce outside the [[House of Assembly of the British Virgin Islands|House of Assembly]] in [[Tortola]], BVI]]
Between 1916 and 1918, during the [[World War I|First World War]], he was a Second Secretary in the British Diplomatic Service.

He later moved to the British Virgin Islands in the 1930s on the advice of his doctors to seek a warmer climate.  He purchased an estate of approximately 230 acres on [[Peter Island]] at Little Harbour and established a small tobacco plantation.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.bviwelcome.com/articles/Peter_Island/|title=Peter Island Then & Now|publisher=BVI Welcome|date=}} </ref>  Subsequently he was elected as a member of First [[House of Assembly of the British Virgin Islands|Legislative Council]] following the [[British Virgin Islands general election, 1950|reintroduction of democracy in 1950]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |title=BVI election and information results 1950–2011 |publisher=BVI Deputy Governor's Office |page=64 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407063531/http://216.197.123.192/Portals/0/Forms/Election%20Information%20and%20Results%201950-2011.pdf |archivedate=2014-04-07 |df= }}</ref>  Although many of Brudenell-Bruce's family had enjoyed long and successful political careers in the United Kingdom, he did not stand in the [[British Virgin Islands general election, 1954|subsequent general election]].  However he was appointed to complete the term of Edwin H. Leonard in the 3rd District when Leonard was unable to continue in 1955, and he served the remainder of the term.

He was the first, and to date the only, [[white people|white person]] to be elected to the [[House of Assembly of the British Virgin Islands|British Virgin Islands legislature]] since the restoration of democracy in 1950.

==Personal==
Brudenell-Bruce was born in 1885 to [[Commodore (Royal Navy)|Commodore]] Lord [[Robert Thomas Brudenell-Bruce]] and his wife, Emma.  He was the grandson of [[Ernest Brudenell-Bruce, 3rd Marquess of Ailesbury]].  He was educated at [[Harrow School]] and married Elsie Drechsel on 29 October 1913.  They were subsequently divorced 1925.  In 1928 he married Sigrid Ammentorp by whom he had six children (David in 1927, Simon in 1928, Barbara in 1928, Marc in 1930, Diana in 1936 and Arabella in 1942).  He died on 13 February 1960 in the British Virgin Islands at the age of 74.<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p2444.htm#i24435|title=John Charles Brudenell-Bruce|publisher=The Peerage|date=23 Mar 2005}}</ref>  He was related to two hereditary titles in the [[peerage of the United Kingdom]]: the [[Marquess of Ailesbury|Marquesses of Ailesbury]] and the [[Earl of Cardigan|Earls of Cardigan]].

==Honors and awards==
In addition to being a [[Order of the British Empire|Member of the Order of the British Empire]], he was a Knight Commander of the [[Order of the Dannebrog]], and a Member of the [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Order of Saint John]].<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p2444.htm#i24435|title=John Charles Brudenell-Bruce|publisher=The Peerage|date=23 Mar 2005}}</ref>

